\series bold 
Activity 2: Radioactive Decay 
\layout Standard

Observation of a sample of radioactive material reveals that the decay of
 the atomic nuclei in the sample is determined by statistical processes.
 In other words, the number of nuclei N
\begin_inset Formula \( _{nuc} \)
\end_inset 

 that decay per unit time is proportional to the number of nuclei in the
 sample.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN_{nuc}}{dt}\propto N_{nuc}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

This expression can be turned into an equality by inserting a constant of
 proportionality 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lambda  \)
\end_inset 

 so
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN_{nuc}}{dt}=-\lambda N_{nuc}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where the minus sign is needed because the number of nuclei N
\begin_inset Formula \( _{nuc} \)
\end_inset 

 decreases with time.
 The decay constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lambda  \)
\end_inset 

 is a characteristic of each atomic nucleus.
 
\layout Standard

(a) It is claimed the solution of the differential equation above describing
 nuclear decay is the following expression.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{nuc}(t)=N_{0}e^{-\lambda t}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 40mm 
Prove this statement by taking the derivative of N
\begin_inset Formula \( _{nuc} \)
\end_inset 

(t) and showing it satisfies the original differential equation.
 Make a sketch of the function and describe it in words.
\layout Standard

(b) The decay of atomic nuclei is often characterized by a quantity known
 as the half-life 
\begin_inset Formula \( \tau  \)
\end_inset 

.
 The half-life is the period of time for one-half of the original sample
 to disappear via radioactive decay.
 This statement can be expressed mathematically in the following way.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{nuc}(t=\tau )=\frac{N_{0}}{2}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Starting with the above expression show that the decay constant 
\begin_inset Formula \( \lambda  \)
\end_inset 

 and the half-life are related by the following equation.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau =\frac{\ln 2}{\lambda }\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard
