Activity 3: Dating the Shroud of Turin 
\layout Standard

The previous example shows how one can use the measured decay rate of an
 atomic nucleus as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

clock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 to determine the passage of time.
 The same concept is used in radiocarbon dating.
 Carbon on the planet Earth consists largely of three isotopes with A =
 12, 13, and 14.
 The most common form is 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{12} \)
\end_inset 

C and only a very small fraction of the carbon is 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C decays via 
\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C 
\begin_inset Formula \( \rightarrow  \)
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

N + 
\begin_inset Formula \( \beta ^{-} \)
\end_inset 

 + 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overline{\nu } \)
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula \( \beta ^{-} \)
\end_inset 

 is an electron and 
\begin_inset Formula \( \overline{\nu } \)
\end_inset 

 is a particle known as a neutrino.
 Notice this decay does NOT preserve the number of protons and neutrons
 in the original nucleus.
 The ratio R of 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C to 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{12} \)
\end_inset 

C on the Earth is 1.30 x 10
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{-12} \)
\end_inset 

 and is roughly constant despite the fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C constantly disappears.
 The ratio is constant because the supply of 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C in the atmosphere is replenished by the reaction of cosmic rays from outer
 space with the nitrogen in the upper atmosphere.
\layout Standard

Living organisms contain large quantities of carbon and are constantly exchangin
g carbon with their surroundings.
 They contain the same proportion of 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C to 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{12} \)
\end_inset 

C as observed in the atmosphere.
 However, this proportion begins to change after the organism dies.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{12} \)
\end_inset 

C remains in the dead body, but the 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C turns into gaseous 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

N (see decay above) and leaves the body.
 Hence, the proportion of 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C decreases with time, and one has a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

clock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 that can be used to determine when an organism died.
 
\layout Standard

The Shroud of Turin is a piece of cloth that bears the image of a man who
 appears to have been crucified.
 It was first displayed in France in the fourteenth century and has been
 kept at the Royal Chapel of Turin Cathedral in a special shrine since 1694.
 Many believe the image on the Shroud is of Christ and the cloth is his
 burial wrap.
 In 1989, three laboratories in Arizona in the USA, Oxford in the UK, and
 Zurich in Switzerland used advanced methods of radiocarbon dating in an
 attempt to determine the age of the Shroud[1].
 The Shroud is woven of cloth made from plants.
 Like a living organism that has died, the 
\begin_inset Formula \( ^{14} \)
\end_inset 

C in the Shroud began to gradually disappear after the plants used to make
 it were harvested.
